}} '''DIG''' is an educational resource owned by the [[York Archaeological Trust]] which aims to increase understanding of [[archaeology]] and related matters. [[File:Church of St Saviour, York.jpg|thumb|St Saviour's Church, now the location of DIG]] DIG is based in [[St Saviour's Church, York|St Saviour's Church]], one of [[York]]'s [[Medieval_parish_churches_of_York#St_Saviour.2C_St_Saviourgate|medieval churches]], which became [[Redundant church|redundant]] in the 1950s.<ref name="NHLE">{{National Heritage List for England| num=1256707 |desc=Church of St Saviour and attached gates and railings |grade=II* |accessdate=10 May 2015}}</ref> It was acquired by the Trust in 1975. Between 1990 and 2005, the building was called the Archaeological Resource Centre. In April 2006, it reopened as DIG.
Activities in which visitors can engage include:
*Discovering techniques used by field archaeologists *Investigating scientific techniques used by archaeologists *Finding out about current archaeological [[Excavation (archaeology)|digs]] and viewing recent finds *Learning more about the [[history of York]]
