{{Infobox writer | name = Victor Langlois | image = LANGLOIS(1861) p012 Victor Langlois.jpg | imagesize = 210px | caption = | birth_date = {{birth date|df=yes|1829|03|20}} | birth_place = [[Dieppe]], France | death_date = {{death date and age|df=yes|1869|05|14|1829|03|20}} | death_place = [[Paris]], France | occupation = Historian, archaeologist, professor, numismatist, and orientalist | movement = | influences = | influenced = | signature = Langlois signature.jpg | website = }} '''Victor Langlois''' (20 March 1829 – 14 May 1869) was a French historian, archaeologist, professor, [[numismatist]], and orientalist who specialized in the study of the [[Middle Ages]]. Langlois was particularly known for his work on [[Armenians|Armenian]] history and culture. He authored more than thirty books on Armenian history.
==Life and work== Victor Langlois was born on rue Sygogne in [[Dieppe]], France on 20 March 1829.<ref name=hachette>{{cite book|title=L'année géographique|date=1870|publisher=Hachette|page=573|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DYBBAAAAcAAJ|language=French}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Lebas|first1=Georges|title=Histoire de la ville de Dieppe de 1830 à 1875: Ornée de gravures|date=1900|publisher=Imp. Centrale et Delevoye Reunies|page=246|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Xj0bAAAAYAAJ|language=French}}</ref> He was educated at the [[École Nationale des Chartes]] and [[Institut national des langues et civilisations orientales]].<ref name=cotta>{{cite book|last1=von Cotta|first1=Johann Friedrich|title=Allgemeine Zeitung München|date=1869|publisher=Allg. Zeitung|pages=3946–7|url=https://books.google.de/books?id=6upDAAAAcAAJ|language=German}}</ref> On 7 May 1852, at the age of 23, he received orders from the French government to visit the predominantly Armenian populated area of [[Cilicia]] in the [[Ottoman Empire]] to carry out studies about historic French and Armenian relations. In particular, Langlois was tasked with studying Armenian-French relations during the [[Crusades]], and to uncover archaeological findings.<ref name=langlois>{{cite book|last1=Langlois|first1=Victor|title=Collection des historiens anciens et modernes de l'Arménie|date=2001|publisher=Fondation Calouste Gulbenkian|location=Lisbonne|isbn=972978597X|page=i|edition=2.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yoklAQAAMAAJ|language=French}}</ref> Remaining in Cilicia until 1853, Langlois published a book on his findings in 1861 entitled ''Voyage dans la Cilicie et dans les montagnes du Taurus'' (''Travels in Cilicia and the Taurus Mountains'').<ref>{{cite book|last1=Uras|first1=Esat|title=The Armenians in history and the Armenian question|date=1988|publisher=Documentary Publications|location=Ankara|isbn=9757555002|page=232|edition=English translation of the rev. and expanded 2.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5AhuAAAAMAAJ}}</ref> [[Terracotta]] figures which he had found in his excavations in the necropolis of Tarsus were exhibited in the [[Louvre]].<ref name=Cyclopaedia>{{cite book | title=The American Cyclopaedia A Popular Dictionary of General Knowledge | last=Ripley | first=George | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9dW7LlAjQggC| page=145| year=1875}}</ref>
Between the year 1857 and 1861, Langlois traveled in Italy in order to discover more historical information concerning the relations between France and Armenia during the Crusades.<ref name=Cyclopaedia /> His other works relate to Egyptian and Georgian numismatics (1852), and to the convent of [[San Lazzaro degli Armeni]] of the Armenian [[Mechitarists|Mekhitarist]] congregation, with an outline of Armenian history and literature (1862).<ref name=Cyclopaedia /> During this time, in 1863, he published a book about the massacres of Armenians by Turks entitled ''Les Armeniens de la Turquie et les Massacres du Taurus'' (''The Armenians of Turkey and the Taurus massacres'').<ref>{{cite book|last1=Langlois|first1=Victor|title=Les Arméniens de la Turquie et les massacres du Taurus|date=1863|publisher=Clays|location=Paris|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hLHwFeBSJ7QC|language=French}}</ref> In 1867 he published ''Le [[Mount Athos|mont Athos]] et ses monasteres'', with a photo-lithographic reproduction of the geography of Ptolemy, of which the Greek manuscript of the 17th century is preserved in that monastery. He became a professor at the [[Collège de France]] in [[Paris]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Petermanns geographische Mitteilungen|date=1870|publisher=J. Perthes|page=31|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HCs6AQAAIAAJ|language=German}}</ref> The first volume of his ''Collection des historiens anciens et modernes de l'Armenie'', a translation from the [[Armenian language]], was published in 1868, under the auspices of the Egyptian-Armenian prime minister [[Nubar Pasha]], but he did not live to complete the work.<ref name=Cyclopaedia />
==Works== Some of Victor Langlois' published works include:<ref name=french>{{cite web|title=Victor LANGLOIS (1829–1869)|url=http://www.acam-france.org/bibliographie/auteur.php?cle=langlois-victor|publisher=Association Culturelle Arménienne de Marne-la-Vallée|language=French}}</ref> *''Rapport sur l'exploration archéologique de la Cilicie et de la Petite-Arménie pendant les années 1852–1853'' (1854) *''Essai historique et critique sur la constitution sociale et politique de l'Arménie sous les rois de la dynastie roupénienne'' (1860) *''Voyage dans la Cilicie et dans les montagnes du Taurus'' (1861) *Étude sur les sources de l'Histoire d'Arménie de Moïse de Khorène (1861) *''Notice sur le couvent arménien de l'île Saint-Lazare de Venise'' (1863) *''Mémoire sur la vie et les écrits de Grégoire Magistros, duc de la Mésopotamie, auteur arménien du XIe siècle'' (1869) *''Collection des historiens anciens et modernes de l'Arménie'' (1869) *''Histoire des Arméniens'' (1880) *''Historicorum Graecorum et Syriorum reliquiae in Armeniorum scriptis servatae'' (1884)
